{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636104","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636104"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:24:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:24:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17566"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17566","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17566"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.38,0.17,0.29,0.04,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10256"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78193"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10256","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10256"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17566"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63599"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7186"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23964"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23969"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26825"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78193","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78193"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe pons contains several important cranial nerve nuclei and serves as an exit point for multiple cranial nerves.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following most accurately describes the location where cranial nerves emerge from the pons?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Facial nerve emerges from the cerebellopontine angle","Trigeminal nerve emerges from the pontomedullary junction","Abducens nerve emerges from the middle of the pons","Trigeminal nerve emerges from the cerebellomedullary junction","Facial nerve emerges from the upper third of the pons"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efacial nerve emerges from the cerebellopontine angle\u003C/strong\u003E, which is the junction between the pons and cerebellum. This is an important anatomical landmark, particularly when considering conditions like acoustic neuromas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrigeminal nerve emerges from the pontomedullary junction\u003C/strong\u003E - The trigeminal nerve actually emerges from the middle of the pons\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbducens nerve emerges from the middle of the pons\u003C/strong\u003E - The abducens nerve emerges from the pontomedullary junction\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrigeminal nerve emerges from the cerebellomedullary junction\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect; the trigeminal nerve emerges from the middle of the pons\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacial nerve emerges from the upper third of the pons\u003C/strong\u003E - The facial nerve emerges more laterally at the cerebellopontine angle\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the emergence points of cranial nerves is crucial for localising lesions and understanding the effects of various pathological processes affecting the brainstem.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The facial nerve (cranial nerve VII) exits the brainstem at the cerebellopontine angle.","The abducens nerve (cranial nerve VI) emerges from the pontomedullary junction.","The trigeminal nerve (cranial nerve V) exits from the middle of the pons."],"referenc